Imputing missing values

Note that there are a number of days/intervals where there are missing values (coded as ). The presence of missing days may introduce bias into some calculations or summaries of the data.

  1. Calculate and report the total number of missing values in the dataset
totalna <- sum(is.na(activity$steps))

A: There are 2304 records with missing steps values

  1. Devise a strategy to imput the missing values in the dataset

A: Missing step values are imputed by using the mean for that time interval Steps: 1. Merge data with the calculated interval mean dataset 2. Create a new column to track imputed values and initiate it equal to the steps column 3. Replace the na values in the new column with the values from the column for the interval mean

  1. Create a new dataset that is equal to the original dataset but with the missing data filled in.
am <- merge(activity,atype, by="interval") %>% tbl_df
am$impsteps <- am$steps
am$impsteps[ is.na(am$impsteps) ] <- am$m[ is.na(am$impsteps) ]
ams <- am %>% select(impsteps,date,interval)
  1. Make a histogram of the total number of steps taken each day and Calculate and report the mean and median total number of steps taken per day.
amday <- ams %>%  group_by(date) %>% summarize(m = mean(impsteps))
ggplot(amday, aes(m)) + geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

impmean <- mean(amday$m)
impmed <- median(amday$m)

Are there differences in activity patterns between weekdays and weekends?

For this part the () function may be of some help here. Use the dataset with the filled-in missing values for this part.

  1. Create a new factor variable in the dataset with two levels weekday and weekend indicating whether a given date is a weekday or weekend day.
ams$weekday <- weekdays(as.Date(ams$date))
## Warning in strptime(xx, f <- "%Y-%m-%d", tz = "GMT"): unknown timezone
## 'default/America/Chicago'
ams$weekend <- "Weekday"
ams$weekend[ams$weekday == "Saturday" | ams$weekday == "Sunday"] <- "Weekend"
ams$weekend <- as.factor(ams$weekend)
  1. Make a panel plot containing a time series plot (i.e. = ) of the 5-minute interval (x-axis) and the average number of steps taken, averaged across all weekday days or weekend days (y-axis).
